    "Reproducibility and replicability Paleyes et al. (2022) discussed some common challenges that practitioners face when deploying ML solutions, and they noted the shortage of reporting deployment experience in academic literature in general.",
    "Gundersen and Kjensmo (2018) defined three levels of reproducibility in relation to ML experiments: Experiment Reproducibility refers to achieving the exact same results when using the same ML system with the same data; Data Reproducibility refers to achieving nearly identical results when using the same data but with a different ML method, ensuring that the insights derived from the data are consistent regardless of the method used; Method Reproducibility refers to achieving similar results or findings when using a different ML method on different data, ensuring that the findings are consistent across various datasets and methods."
